If the blade is thicker, you can do a vine and thorn or an arrowhead design instead. This is a design element and is optional. Mark the blade in 1/4" (.635cm) increments. Most designs use the same measurement. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/0d/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-7Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-7Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/0d/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-7Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-7Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Use the triangular file just to put in the initial notches, so the round file won't slide all over the place. Pick one side to start and notch every other one. Turn it around and do the other side. Then switch to a small chainsaw file. Try to keep it at around a 20 degree angle and file almost to the opposite edge of the knife. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a8/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-7Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-7Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/a8/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-7Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-7Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Use a large chainsaw file to make the notches wider and then switch to the flat file and round off the shape edges. If the blade is only 1/16" thick, you might be cutting it close with the files. There will be some minor uh-ohs and scratches, but some 150 grit sandpaper wrapped around the file will take care of them. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/8b/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-7Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-7Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/8b/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-7Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-7Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Normally you can use a grinder but the hook on this particular type of blade prevents that. Try to leave a flat edge roughly 1/64" wide. During the buffing part, when you use a leather buffing wheel and some buffing compound, the edge will form.Use a small C clamp on the front of the grinder to set the angle. Then slowly pull the knife from left to right. Turn the knife facing the other way and do the same for the other side. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/10/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-8Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-8Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/10/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-8Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-8Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Lock the belt sander in a vise, upside down and just run the blade over it at about a twenty degree angle. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/c3/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-8Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-8Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/c3/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-8Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-8Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Most of the blades have a Rockwell hardness of 35 so they will need to be heat treated and tempered to hold an edge. Most industrial grade blades are hard enough and do not need to be treated (but if it is too hard, it will not sharpen easily).Run a large stove burner on high. This is not hot enough to get the blade to around 1500F, so use a MAPP gas torch and the burner together. That will take it to a non-magnetic state. Note that the temperatures needed to temper will vary based on the metal. L6 (sawblades), L7 ( large sawmill blades) and tool steel type O-1 are probably the easiest for beginners. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/c7/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-9Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-9Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/c7/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-9Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-9Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Once it gets hot enough for the magnet not to stick, hold the temp for a minute to make sure it will be an even heat treat. There's no picture of this being done because it is hard to hold a camera, a torch and pliers with a magnet. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/4b/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-9Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-9Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/4b/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-9Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-9Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Quench in vegetable oil that is about 130F for 1 minute. Do not quench in the house with metal any thicker than a saw blade. Thicker metal retains more heat and will make a large plume of smoke and possibly ignite and boil over the oil. Instead, keep it hot with your torch while you go outside to quench it. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/1e/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-9Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-9Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/1e/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-9Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-9Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Wipe the oil off the blade and throw it in the oven at 525F for one hour. Do yourself a favor and lay it on some aluminum foil first, that way there are no knife shapes burned into the wife's favorite cookie sheet. It will come out black and a little flaky but some 120 grit sandpaper will take care of that. If you don't wipe it down, the oil congeals on the blade and forms a very sticky mess that is a pain to get off. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/9f/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-9Bullet4.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-9Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/9/9f/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-9Bullet4.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-9Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

This particular example uses blood wood.Rip off a couple pieces that are just wide enough to feel comfortable on the knife and trace the pattern for the handle onto the wood. Make sure the sides that touch the metal are perfectly flat so you get the best fit. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/38/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-10Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-10Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/38/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-10Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-10Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Run the piece of wood through the bandsaw and cut them about 1/16" larger than the handle pattern. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/72/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-10Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-10Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/72/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-10Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-10Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Once you get them lined up with the handle,  mark the holes for the handles on the wood with a sharpie marker and throw a piece of tape around the wood to hold it together while drilling the holes. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/ee/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-10Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-10Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/ee/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-10Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-10Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

To help keep them from slipping around and getting the holes out of alignment, drill one hole and add a pin, then drill the second hole and add the second pin, and finally the third. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/5d/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-10Bullet4.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-10Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/5d/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-10Bullet4.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-10Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Switch to a sanding drum and remove the tool marks and round the edges. While you are at it, you can sand in a couple of finger grooves at the front (not shown). {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/31/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-10Bullet5.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-10Bullet5.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/3/31/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-10Bullet5.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-10Bullet5.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Cover the handles with tape except for where the adhesive will be. While  taping, press down where the pins will be inserted. That makes it easier to find the holes and insert the pins while everything is covered with epoxy. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/ea/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-11Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-11Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/ea/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-11Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-11Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Use industrial grade heavy duty epoxy. Mix it on old plastic lids. When the leftover is dry, it peels right off and the lid can be reused. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/ae/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-11Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-11Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/a/ae/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-11Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-11Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Insert pins and clamp. Even if the glue label says no clamping is needed, it will help to create a thin glue line. Wait overnight. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d4/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-11Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-11Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d4/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-11Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-11Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

It brings out a razor sharp edge. Some caution should be used when you are using the leather and cloth buffing wheels, especially with a guthook. They can get caught on the blade and hook while spinning. At high speeds, there is no reaction time, the blade can fly across the room or come all the way around the wheel and hit your hand. It helps to angle the leading edge of the blade away from the wheel. There are several other options as well:
Use a belt sander with fine grit sandpaper to shine and sand the blade. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b1/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-15Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-15Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b1/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-15Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-15Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

The next option is to use a cloth buffing wheel to put a mirror grade shine on the blades and use sharpening stones to apply the final edge. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/17/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-15Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-15Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/17/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-15Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-15Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

The third option is to apply a hand rubbed finish. Take a piece of medium grit sandpaper and rub the blade from the guard/handle to the tip. No back and forth motion. When that grit will no longer shine the blade, switch to a finer grit and repeat. This is very time consuming. You could spend as much as eight hours working from a low 120 grit to a high 1000 grit. Stopping at 320 grit will leave a satin finish, whereas stopping at 1000 grit will leave a mirror finish. If the blade is deeply scratched, which happens sometimes, hand rubbing helps. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/67/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-15Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-15Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/67/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-15Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-15Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Another alternative is called draw filing. Clamp the blade to a flat piece of metal and lock the metal into a vise. Place a large bastard mill file flat on the blade and pull it toward you. This will slowly work the scratches out. Don't go in the opposite direction--it works, but is more dangerous. While exerting pressure on the file and blade, if your hands or the file slips, you could be impaled by the blade. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e7/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-15Bullet4.jpg/v4-460px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-15Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e7/Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-15Bullet4.jpg/v4-760px-Make-a-Guthook-Knife-from-an-Old-Saw-Blade-Step-15Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}
